    {
      "id": "3f6e7c6c134a9dcae50baecbd2b7802fd21c81ee",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 06:56:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nIn addition to actual races, I just thought of additional scenario of open-unlinked files access where nlink is 0, but the file is opened on another client and is being read, if it's the writer that wrote data and then unlinked the file - the reader would miss the write.\n\nIs this ok?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "4f3e4cbf78e3ac7dbb8070c95e55c65fb6b7a961",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 443,
        "name": "Andrew Perepechko",
        "email": "andrew.perepechko@hpe.com",
        "username": "panda"
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 11:23:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "c65d03b673cbd7a93565e37ef0adb1d11af77794",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 15:43:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nSo you are suggesting a situation where there is dirty data waiting to be written out and it's lost because of an unlink?  Dirty data that would normally be readable to another client because it's still got the file open?\n\nThat's a real race condition, but it exists already, I believe.  Currently, if we do a getattr, we find the value of nlink is zero - So if someone with this file open does a stat then closes it, this destruction would occur.\n\nImagine a library that writes data then does a stat after the write.  That's not that rare, and once that library closed the file, it would lose its data.  That's not affected one way or another by this mod.\n\nPerhaps I'm misunderstanding how we stay safe from this today.  (Also, if there are dirty pages, there is an LDLM write lock.  I think that probably doesn't affect the race you're mentioning, though.)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "34f541835cb2b9fcce37115f8499d4943be66fe4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 20:06:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "cd7b391c5e0f1d46898b881ff6274c2c24ec3484",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 20:06:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: -Code-Review\n\nerr, not what I wanted to do",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "e18a2f6d61471a118a1b6cc851dc9f36dfa3f5ae",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 20:24:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nSo ldlm lock indeed does not help us here, but shadow dug out this bit in ll_delete_inode:\n\n        if (S_ISREG(inode->i_mode) && lli->lli_clob != NULL)\n                /* It is last chance to write out dirty pages,\n                 * otherwise we may lose data while umount */\n                cl_sync_file_range(inode, 0, OBD_OBJECT_EOF, CL_FSYNC_LOCAL, 1);\n\n\nThis will flush dirty pages out for deleted files (I am not sure why this is important in umount, came from LU-5584). Of course the downside here is every unlinked file is not really discarded - good for this race, bad for other reasons.\n\nSo I guess at least the data loss I imagined does not exist which is good.\n\nOr is it? I am loooking for the place where I definitely remember nlink = 0 on iput = invalidate all pages and cannot see it, so I wonder what path does that take.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "004634b4030705dcabcde9d1ec44ad8d121b371a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 20:50:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI think the code in question is just the evict code, which calls ll_delete_inode for Lustre (at least, in the upstream kernel, didn't verify in master).  When the nlink and i_count drop to zero, the inode will go through this path.\n\nAt least, that's what I'm familiar with.  And that's the same path you're looking at.\n\nLook at 'evict' fs/inode.c, that's the vfs bit.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "ec7508558c643c355e73e0e47f6a4c0365e08cb7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2017-10-24 20:52:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI mean, sorry, I think that's the code which normally does that cleanup on unlink you described.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "f47bad8235cda83ae96e2107017f6182acb67344",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2017-10-25 00:54:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2\n\nI guess iput_final()->evict() is the path.\n\nIt was a lot more explicit before, and now there are just some checks about writeback.\n\nAnyway I think that drop inode code makes this patch fine.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "e90158340072b81d34ac3c82ce7c7b9d6564f78f",
      "date": "2017-10-25 00:54:36.000000000",
      "message": "Change has been successfully cherry-picked as 947b22b08d3725852a811a9e330562dd986d7336 by Oleg Drokin",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    }
  ],
  "current_revision_number": 4,
  "current_revision": "947b22b08d3725852a811a9e330562dd986d7336",
